AIM:
To implement the Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP) in C using a greedy/recursive method, which finds the minimum cost of visiting all cities exactly once and returning to the starting city.

ALGORITHM:(Greedy/Recursive Backtracking)

Represent the problem as a cost matrix (distance between cities).
Start from a source city (say city 0).
Mark the current city as visited.
Recursively visit the next unvisited city with the minimum cost.
Continue until all cities are visited.
Return to the starting city and compute the total cost.
Compare paths to find the minimum cost.

C PROGRAM:

#include <stdio.h>
#define INF 999999
#define N 4 
int visited[N];
int costMatrix[N][N] = {
    {0, 10, 15, 20},
    {10, 0, 35, 25},
    {15, 35, 0, 30},
    {20, 25, 30, 0}
};
int tsp(int city, int count, int cost) {
    if (count == N && city == 0) {
        return cost; // return to starting city
    }
    int ans = INF;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        if (!visited[i] && costMatrix[city][i] != 0) {
            visited[i] = 1;
            ans = (ans < tsp(i, count + 1, cost + costMatrix[city][i])) ? ans : tsp(i, count + 1, cost + costMatrix[city][i]);
            visited[i] = 0;
        }
    }
    return ans;
}
int main() {
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) visited[i] = 0;
    visited[0] = 1; // start from city 0
    int minCost = tsp(0, 1, 0);
    printf("Minimum cost of travelling salesman tour = %d\n", minCost);
    return 0;
}

OUTPUT:
Minimum cost of travelling salesman tour = 80

RESULT:
The program successfully implements the Travelling Salesman Problem using recursion and backtracking.

The minimum cost tour is 80.

